      "id": 1,
      "text": "Spanish explorer Juan Rodríguez Cabrillo first spotted Carmel’s white‑sand beach and pine forest in 1542, marking the area’s earliest European record.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.carmelchamber.org/carmel-history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Mission San Carlos Borromeo de Carmelo, founded in 1770, moved to Carmel Valley in 1771 under Junípero Serra’s direction.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5,
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmel-by-the-Sea%2C_California"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Following the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, artists, writers, and musicians escaped to Carmel, turning it into a creative enclave.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmel-by-the-Sea%2C_California"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Carmel Free Library opened in 1906, lending books from a modest redwood building that still echoes its early days.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
